<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Else Matters Besides Fabric Weight?</h2>

  <h3>1. Size and Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    The cloth needs to cover the bed properly and reach the ground well enough to trap warmth.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Edge Sealing</h3>
  <p>
    Gaps at the bottom let warm air escape and reduce protection.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Hoops or Support</h3>
  <p>
    Support helps create a better air space and can keep heavier cloth from resting directly on tender plants.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Reuse and Handling</h3>
  <p>
    A cloth you can deploy quickly and store easily may be more useful than a theoretically better one that becomes a hassle.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Buy</h2>

  <p>
    If you want one frost cloth for general vegetable-garden use, start with a medium-weight option. It is usually the best all-around choice for typical spring and fall protection.
  </p>

  <p>
    Go lighter if your main job is covering against mild frost and you want something easy to handle often. Go heavier if you regularly protect tender crops through colder shoulder-season events and are prepared for the extra bulk and tradeoffs.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Buy for your usual risk, not your most extreme hypothetical night.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    The best frost cloth for most vegetable gardens is usually a medium-weight fabric that gives meaningful protection without becoming overly heavy or inconvenient.
  </p>

  <p>
    Lightweight cloth is excellent for mild frost and frequent use. Heavier cloth is worth considering when the risk is colder and the plants are more tender. The right choice depends less on the label alone and more on how you actually garden.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    The best frost cloth is the one that matches your real conditions and gets used when it matters.
  </p>
</section>